The Governor of Rivers State who is also a presidential hopeful in the 2023 general election under the platform of the People’s Democratic  Party (PDP) has said that he will take power back from the All Progressives Congress  (APC) to the main opposition party in 2023. Governor Wike made this declaration when he paid a visit to the leaders and members of the party at the office of Chief Bode George, former Deputy National Chairman of the party on Sunday. The presidential hopeful stated that they were not going to beg but would take back power because the power belongs to the PDP. He said, “I have the integrity. I have the capacity and the tenacity to make things happen. We cannot allow things to be the way they have been. I will go and take back the power. “We are not going to beg.  The power belongs to PDP. So we will go and take back the power,” Chief Bode George who was the host, thanked the members for coming to receive the visitors, stressing that Wike has told them in clear terms that when it comes to integrity, and capacity, he is there. “He has the strength, capacity and integrity to do the job. We need a bright person who will take us out of the doldrums and lead us to where we should be. The Atona Odua of Yorubaland took the time to pray for Wike while stating that the public is waiting for the PDP and advised party members to be united. POLL “The people outside are more in number and are waiting to know whom they can trust. We must be United and respect the constitution of our party to be able to take power,” he said. Those who were at the meeting include the governor of Oyo State, Seyi Makinde, a former governor of Benue State, Senator Gabriel Suswam, leaders of the party from the South-west region,  Soji Adagunodo, deputy national vice-chairman South-West and other leaders of the party.